segments.text: Other good teachers?
M.H.
Byron.
What did he teach?
He was a research man for the Deadhead.
He was the one that took over the cotton stripper.
He, he, that was his job for years.
And he taught me a lot of stuff.
How to, we tore batteries down and repaired them and put them back together and car batteries.
And charged them up and they had a whole system there and they kind of, he taught me to use a torch.
Did your dad deliberately teach you much?
He was a hard test master.
But did he instruct?
Yes, he did.
Is that right?
He did.
Now, you didn't have any classes taught by him, did you?
Yes.
You did?
What was it?
It was farm instruction.
And what grade did you make?
Do you remember?
Eight.
I designed the building on...
You know these Quonset humps that they had?
When Dad said, he said, I want you to design one.
See, Dad went down there on the river during the Depression, and he bought 150 acres for $10 an acre.
That same land today, you can't buy it for less than 50 grand.
Yeah, yeah.
So he said, we'll decide a building down there.
So he gave me, that was my project when I was a senior.
And I designed the thing.
And Dad always wore a suit, the vest, and he had a
and a pocket watch on this side, and some sort of a little thing over here.
That might have been a Masonic, a Masonic thing.
It was either a Masonic or a S-A-H-E, you know, Aggie Dream Association.
But I think it might have been a Masonic.
I found out here just recently.
And so he had a chain across there.
Well, he told me to build a building like those closets with a, in a catenary.
You don't know what a catenary is, do you?
Catener?
Catenary.
No, sir.
Catenary.
Well, those wires on a suspension.
Oh, I see.
Okay.
That's a catenary.
Okay.
It's always in tension.
If you turn it upside down, it'll always be in compression.
You got no other?
So we designed it.
So the reason for asking for that,
He came in there and we were drawing, we drew it up.
We had to draw this thing in there.
Big curve at the top.
Yeah, big curve.
So I said, I just walked up there one day, I said, can I have your watch and chain?
We went over there and hung it on the wall.
And I got someone to help me, and we drew that thing exactly the width that we wanted it.
That's the way we got the catnip.
That's the catnip.
And that was to support those upright curve, those arches?
Yeah.
So then he says, now, you go take that over and have a, he had a lot of rapport with those people in the San Ling Ling.
And he said, go take it.
I think he said, I don't remember.
I know what a man looked like.
He was a big guy.
And I told him what I wanted.
And he said, yeah, set it down there, and I'll look at it.
And he went through some calculations on it later.
And he said, come back in a couple of days, and I'll have it for you.
He went through some calculations on them, and then he told me that that thing wouldn't stand up and wouldn't win.
He told me how to fix it.
So here's your catenary like this.
He said, put a floor across here.
It was a two-story building.
It wasn't big enough for a two-story.
He said, put a floor across here and put some suspensions right here from that roof down here to hold that floor.
He said, he'll see it.
It's strong enough now.
Because you made use of both sides of that.
You transferred it over.
Now, in all of your A&M undergraduate years, you never...
uh, wavered about being an engineer.
That was your plan all the time.
That's correct.
All right.
And, uh... See, I was raised in a, in a, in a collegiate family.
Sure.
Sure.
And, uh, did your dad encourage that goal for you?
Oh, yes.
Okay.
Now, when you graduated, how well prepared did you think A&M had made you as an engineer?
You felt comfortable.
When you got to Iowa State for your graduate work, did you find that you were, compared to other graduate students, were you well?
We were well prepared.
Now they were tough.
They were tougher than we'd been used to.
Because old Van Giese, he was a German.
And he taught that same course.
And then I went out.
And so we got in the meeting.
The last thing they do for you is they get all your teachers in there into a session with you.
And I had built a building out there that had a 40-foot span on it.
And so I had done some, I had taken a course in steel construction.
That's one that I had to take.
And this prof, he said, did you treat that thing?
I had some braces on it.
did you create that thing as a plate girder or did you depend on those trusses?
And I said, I really depend on those trusses in there.
But he said, do you?
And I said, you're right, it could have been a full plate girder.
And so I remember that thing.
Now, you finished at Iowa State and then came back to A&M?
Yeah, that was in 38.
And you joined the faculty then?
No, worked for my father.
Worked for your father.
For a year.
For a year.
And was he, he died the next year?
Yes.
It was that, the fall of that year in 38.
He was in Dallas one day and he was walking down the street and his hand just opened and dropped his suitcase.
Heart attack?
No.
And that's what we didn't know about.
So it got worse.
And that was it, yeah.
It'd be in the fall of 38.
So then my wife, he wanted to go.
He said, take me to Mayo Clinic.
To Mayo Clinic?
And so I did.
We did.
We got on training.
We went through.
St. Louis, and that train was running a hundred miles an hour.
And that thing went across from there.
I said over there in time, I know what that thing was doing, but it was clicking and that rail was too fast.
And so they got him up there and
They looked at him and they really didn't know what was going on with him.
They did not know.
There was no way they could tell.
He had some impairment with his hand.
And so we were...
So then what happened was that the hardware and implement association, they always put on a big deal convention in Houston in the late January.
And it was getting close to that.
It was cold, the blue blades were thick.
And so then I decided that, no, he decided to call Mother and have her come up here and stay with me, and you got to go run that convention.
Yeah, I was.
I bet I did.
We got the mother up there, and just before that happened, well, he lost the sense in the side of his face.
See, they didn't know where it was.
They didn't know whether it was in a muscle or in the spine or someplace else.
But when he lost the sensation in his face, they knew it was in his head.
Mm-hmm.
And so she stayed with him and finally brought him home.
And that was in, he died in November of that year.
Of 39.
Yeah, and mother took care of him.
And built a bed down in the sun porch, and she had help, took care of him.
All right, on a happier note, when did you meet your wife?
about right then, about that.
It was a little before that.
It was in, when I got back in 30, yeah, 38.
When you got back from Iowa State?
Yeah, I got back in September.
And we had started to build that, we had started, Dan and I had started to write that handbook for hang engineers.
And so then,
It had a dance over there.
So I wanted to go to the dance.
So I asked Madge Wallace.
I don't know if you ever knew her or not.
It's Wallace, Wallace Printing Company, but she was a, her name just, she married a Wallace.
Her name was Madge Nettles.
She had worked with Dan when he was in the,
the resettlement administration.
See, Dad spent several years right in there while I was at Ames.
He ran the resettlement administration for the government here.
And that was one of the times.
And so then I asked Madge, can you find me a date?
And so she went and got her roommate, which was Margaret.
And her roommate where?
In a rooming house right across from the Catholic school there in Bride.
Oh, okay.
And what was this roommate doing?
Was she working?
She was a teacher.
Oh, okay.
In Bryan High School.
And where had she grown up?
In Hubbard, Texas.
Hubbard, Texas.
Gone to college where?
In Baylor.
Baylor, okay.
She finished high school a year ahead of time.
She finished Baylor in three years.
And so you go out with this Baptist girl to the dance.
No, she wasn't a Baptist.
Oh, I thought if she went to Baylor, she might have been.
No, she went there.
She went there, and they gave her a job.
She ran a switchboard.
That was her job, and that was primarily due to this woman.

The roommate she had, which was married with the principal of the school down here, and that's how she got, she first taught at, Margaret first taught two years at Adaska, and then she came down here.
Her roommate,
told her husband, and the mortgage was available up there, and so they bumped into each other one day, and he said, come on down here.
So she went to work down there, and so this was in the fall, and we got together a little over about the middle of the year,
Then I had to go to take care of this convention down here.
And then later we decided to get married.
So y'all got married when?
January 11, 1939.
And left immediately for the ASA convention in Minneapolis.
We drove a car.
And then we went from there to Washington, D.C., which I thought would work for the I.R.E.M.
Now, after that, did you ever work for A.N.M.
again?
No, no.
Yes, I did after World War II.
What did you do?
Mother, I was discharged from Thailand.
came home.
Of course we had, by that time, we had even a child, because the oldest girl was born in Chicago during World War II.
And Margaret worked in the personnel department for the University of Chicago.
And so we came home and we were just sitting around down there and the REA wanted to send me to the state of Washington and I said I didn't want to go.
And so I just never did answer their questions.
And so
uh, the director of the Inuring Experiment Station, a good friend of ours, a good friend of Mother's too, and she, he called Mother up and says, has Bill come home yet?
Yeah, he's been here about a week.
Send him up here.
Now who was that?
Oh.
Remember his name?
Yeah.
You'll think of it in a minute.
Go ahead.
Yeah.
Anyways, we just walked in up there.
And he said, I got to have somebody to administrative assistant.
So I got hired right then.
They just made out the papers and hired me.
And so then I did a lot of, for them,
I did a bunch of different things.
It was just an administrative job.
I was just taking care for the vice director.
I think he was the vice director.
Describe this campus right after the war was over as the veterans start pouring in here.
What was it like?
Oh, they converted Walden Hall to some apartments.
And then the women came in there pregnant.
How long did it take to get the temporary buildings near Kyle Field and the old, near the old, oh what, where the poor boys lived during the Depression?
How long did it take them to move those in?
Did they do that quickly?
They were already there.
They were there way back.
Didn't they put in some new temporary structures down there also?
They were mostly houses that were on the
on the street there on Bush Avenue.
Okay.
To the, to the, to between there and the Wellborn, you know.
Mm-hmm.
There's a whole bunch right in there.
Yeah, yeah.
And they were saying some constructed elsewhere, and then a large home would be taken over, and they would, they would, the county would, would get together.
Mm-hmm.
And they would, they would kind of
have an association of some sort that, and they were supplying money, and more than that, goods, whatever, and food.
But then after World War II, Usually one of the, there was a mother came with them.
After World War II, weren't there a whole bunch of
Quick, new, temporary buildings for the veterans to live in?
Vet village type of things?
Yeah, they moved those up.
They moved them up there on the old Aging Farms where it was.
Okay.
All those things up there were constructions.
They were, now they're permanent buildings, but they moved in.
Now called College View.
Yeah, College View.
But they were temporary.
Where did those buildings come from?
Did they come from the Air Force Base?
Bryan Field?
I don't think they did.
There wasn't enough out there.
See, Bryan Field was a,
was a training base for instrument flying.
And they had taken over the college, the Easterwood here.
See, Easterwood was built under, by the FAA.
So if a military wanted it, they'd just give them a dollar and they got control of it.
That's what happened.
And they used it principally for training students to land and take off under instrument conditions.
And so that's what that was for.
Now the vet, but the veteran students changed this community, didn't they?
They did, they did.
Friends were, and they, they, they put in a, a, right in Speesa Hall in the,
They put in another eating joint down there from the side.
You went in that side door.
And that's where the people from Walden Hall ate.
You had to eat over there.
And were those veterans good students?
Wonderful students.
That's what I've always heard.
That's what I've always heard.
All right, you worked for then the college.
How long?
14 years, up to 1960.
Okay, and were you with the Ag Extension Experiment Station all those years?
What happened was that at first I was an administrative assistant.
I had, I had a whole five or six stenographers.
They brought me
engineering bulletins that were in manuscript form.
And I had all these people there.
Then I'd take them, had to take them over to Austin to a Bible printer who had estate contracts at the publisher.
They got through.
Now that was one of the jobs I had.
Then I had other
Everything came up with a job of some sort.
So then you had an estate required that you couldn't have an escalation cross in anything you bought.
I mean, you had to price.
So they wanted a motor for the wind tunnel.
Where are we going to get a motor for the wind tunnel?
Well, we scurried around and asked a lot of questions, and finally found out that there was a rewind company, and we wanted 2,000 horsepower engines.
And he came back at us and said,

Well, he could get us one, and it turned out what it was was a big generator, a 2,000 horsepower generator that was hooked to those big engines on the 29s for test work in a plant in Chicago, Illinois.

that's where those engines were tested and they were run six hours on that and torn down and then they were put back together and rerun well he bought one this guy was rewind man bought one of those things rewinded into a motor and gave us a price and we bought it and we shipped down here and
old Frank Brown, old Frank Brown is his name, he was the college electrician.
That thing had a starting circuit on it was 2300 volts.
And that's all it had, that's the only piece of line they had going out there.
And they could only run it at night because we didn't have enough fire to pull them.
Which is common in most, uh, uh, wind tunnels.
Mm-hmm.
They, they absorb so much of our, you know, even their own air.
The one that, I know the one up there in the right field that we run at night, 40,000 horsepower.
Now, during these years, where was Ag Experiment State, uh, where were y'all located?
Well, we, in 1935, we, uh, 34, we got in the Aggie Union Building.
All right, and was this all the time?
Huh?
No, I'm sorry, I didn't mean Aggie Union.
No, you were working for the Experiment Station or the Extensions?
Yeah, uh-huh.
Where was the Experiment Station located?
Uh, in the, uh...
geology building.
Now this is after World War II.
Yeah, it had a little top on it.
Who was the director when you went to work in 45 or 46?
What the heck, the old doctor, he was a nice, oh, and then later, oh yeah, what was his name, he came in there.
That's the second one.
All right, now y'all reported to the dean of agriculture?
Dean of engineering.
And who was the dean then?
Benson.
No, Benson wasn't dean yet.
Was it Calhoun?
Might have been.
It didn't bother me.
I was too damn busy.
Did, how did you feel about?
Oh, yeah, we had another one.
We had Langford, not the one you know, but they had a man called Langford that he was working on freight race.
That was in there.
That was mixed up in there.
So I had a, you know, I didn't like that.

And across the street, across the, that was on the east side of the, in the fourth floor up there, and on the other side there was, was Dr. Lindsey, who was head of the, came from the Lindsey and Ingram department.
And he had three boys, one of them a doctor, one of them would take care of your life, your eye case, and one of them a lawyer.
I knew all three of them.
I knew the old man too.
Who was the A&M president when you got back?
I don't know.
Gilchrist?
I guess Gilchrist was.
Were you aware of that march the students made when the Corps marched on his house to try to revolt?
He was trying to crack down on them to quit hazing the freshmen so long, and they tried to confront him.
Where was he?
He was in the college residence up there?
He was living in the president's house, yes, sir, and they marched on that house one night.
I don't know anything about that.
During those years, in the late 40s and 50s, did you and your colleagues think A&M was making progress?
Oh, yes.
We knew for a fact that they were going to do two things.
They were going to let the niggers in, and they were going to let the women in.
I made a million old men mad, because I said, which do you want first?
You want the nigger in there, or you want the nigger in there?
You want the woman in there.
And, of course, they preferred the woman.
